66. Plus One

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> plusOne(vector<int>& digits) {
        for(int i = digits.size()-1; i>=0; i--)
        {
            if(digits[i] != 9)
            {
                digits[i] += 1;
                return digits;
            }
            else
            {
                digits[i] = 0;
            }
        }

        digits.insert(digits.begin(),1);
        return digits;
    }
};


int* plusOne(int* digits, int digitsSize, int* returnSize) {
    int* res = (int*)calloc((digitsSize + 1),sizeof(int));
    for(int i = 0; i < digitsSize; i++) res[i] = digits[i];
    for(int i = digitsSize - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        if(res[i] != 9) {
            res[i] += 1;
            *returnSize = digitsSize;
            return res;
        }else res[i] = 0;
    }
    res[0] = 1;
    *returnSize = digitsSize+1;
    return res;
}


Intuition
The number is stored as an array of digits, where: The last element is the least significant digit Adding 1 behaves exactly like manual addition


Key observations:
If the last digit is not 9, we can simply increment the last digit alone and that's the answer.

If a digit is 9, adding 1 makes it 0 and produces a carry.

The carry may continue moving left.

If all digits are 9, we need one extra digit at the front
(e.g., 999 â†’ 1000).
So, the idea is to: Start adding from the rightmost digit and stop as soon as no carry is needed.

Approach
Traverse the array from right to left.
For each digit: 
If the digit is not 9: Increment it by 1 Return the array immediately (no carry left)
If the digit is 9: Set it to 0 and continue to the next digit (carry forward) 
If the loop finishes:
It means all digits were 9 Create a new array of size n + 1 Set the first digit to 1 Return the new array


Complexity
Time complexity:
O(1) - Best Case
O(n) - Worst case (When all elements are nine in array)

Space complexity:
O(1)
